<TITLE> Mobile teledensity up 1,585% in five years </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 27 (bdnews24.com) - Mobile telephone density in Bangladesh has increased by 1,585 percent in five years -- between January 2002 and January 2007, according to a government document. Mobile teledensity in the country, merely one percent in January 2002 touched 16.85 percent in January 2007, according to the Bangladesh Economic Review 2007 published recently by the government. Although more than 90 percent of the population live under the coverage of mobile, only 17 out of 100 people use mobile phone in Bangladesh. Up to January 2007, the number of mobile subscribers had reached 2.18 crore, according to the review. The Asian Development Bank, in a recent estimate, has said that the number of mobile subscribers in Bangladesh would double to 44 million in the next two years. Pacific Bangladesh Telecom Ltd. launched first mobile phone using analog AMPS technology in 1993. Later it migrated to digital CDMA option. In November 1996, licenses to operate cellular mobile phone networks were issued, and GrameenPhone, Telekom Malaysia International Bangladesh Ltd (Aktel) and Sheba Telecom (Pvt.) Ltd entered the market. Later, Teletalk (government-owned) and Warid Telecom were licenced to operate in Bangladesh. Sheba Telecom Ltd was acquired by Orascom in September 2004 and re-branded to Banglalink. Mentionably, all the operators, except Teletalk, are joint ventures in which Bangladesh units collaborate with foreign companies. The Economic Review 2007 also said that the government had issued 37 licences in the private sector for the operation fixed telephones to meet the growing telephone demands of the country. bd
